## ⚡ Caching & Production Performance

A production app must be fast. Caching is the #1 technique for reducing latency and server load. This lesson covers caching strategies at every layer — browser, CDN, API, and database.

---

## 1️⃣ What is Caching?

Caching stores the result of an expensive operation so that future requests can return the stored result instantly instead of recomputing.

```
Without cache:
  User Request → Server → Database → Process → Response (500ms)

With cache:
  User Request → Cache hit → Response (5ms) ⚡
```

---

## 2️⃣ HTTP Caching Headers

Control how browsers and CDNs cache responses:

```javascript
// Express — set cache headers
res.setHeader('Cache-Control', 'public, max-age=3600')         // Cache for 1 hour
res.setHeader('Cache-Control', 'private, max-age=0')           // Don't cache
res.setHeader('Cache-Control', 'no-cache')                     // Validate with server
res.setHeader('Cache-Control', 'public, max-age=31536000, immutable') // Cache 1 year (static assets)

// ETag — content-based caching
const etag = generateEtag(data)
res.setHeader('ETag', etag)

// Client sends ETag back
if (req.headers['if-none-match'] === etag) {
  return res.status(304).send()  // Not Modified — serve from browser cache
}
```

---

## 3️⃣ Redis — In-Memory Cache

Redis stores key-value pairs in memory (microsecond read times). Perfect for:
- Caching database query results
- Session storage
- Rate limiting
- Job queues

```bash
npm install ioredis
```

```javascript
const Redis = require('ioredis')
const redis = new Redis(process.env.REDIS_URL)

// Cache a database query
async function getUser(id) {
  const cacheKey = `user:${id}`

  // 1. Check cache first
  const cached = await redis.get(cacheKey)
  if (cached) {
    return JSON.parse(cached)  // ⚡ Cache hit — no DB query
  }

  // 2. Cache miss — query database
  const user = await User.findById(id)
  if (!user) return null

  // 3. Store in cache for 1 hour (TTL = 3600 seconds)
  await redis.setex(cacheKey, 3600, JSON.stringify(user))

  return user
}

// Invalidate cache when data changes
async function updateUser(id, data) {
  const updated = await User.findByIdAndUpdate(id, data, { new: true })
  await redis.del(`user:${id}`)  // Bust cache
  return updated
}
```

---

## 4️⃣ Cache Invalidation Strategies

The hardest problem in caching — when to clear stale data:

| Strategy | How | Use When |
|---|---|---|
| **TTL (Time-To-Live)** | Auto-expire after N seconds | Data changes predictably |
| **Cache Aside** | App checks cache, then DB | General purpose |
| **Write-Through** | Update cache AND DB together | Consistency needed |
| **Event-Based** | Invalidate on data change events | Real-time accuracy needed |

```javascript
// TTL-based
await redis.setex('leaderboard', 300, JSON.stringify(data))  // 5 min

// Event-based invalidation on update
async function updateCourse(id, data) {
  await Course.findByIdAndUpdate(id, data)

  // Invalidate related caches
  await redis.del(`course:${id}`)
  await redis.del(`courses:all`)
  await redis.del(`instructor:${data.instructorId}:courses`)
}
```

---

## 5️⃣ Next.js Caching Layers

Next.js has its own multi-level caching system:

```typescript
// 1. Request Memoization — deduplicate same fetch in one render
const user1 = await fetch('/api/me')  // Database called
const user2 = await fetch('/api/me')  // Cache hit — same request, no DB call

// 2. Data Cache — persist across requests
const res = await fetch('/api/courses', {
  next: { revalidate: 3600 }  // Cache for 1 hour (ISR)
})

// 3. Full Route Cache — cache entire rendered page (SSG/ISR)
export const revalidate = 60  // Regenerate page every 60s

// 4. Router Cache — client-side cache on navigation
// Next.js caches page content on client for fast back/forward
```

---

## 6️⃣ Database Query Optimization

```javascript
// Use indexes — without index, MongoDB scans every document
userSchema.index({ email: 1 })       // Create index
userSchema.index({ role: 1, createdAt: -1 })  // Compound

// Select only needed fields (projection)
const users = await User.find().select('name email avatar')  // Don't fetch password, etc.

// Use lean() — returns plain JS objects (faster, less memory)
const users = await User.find().lean()

// Paginate — never return all records
const users = await User.find()
  .skip((page - 1) * limit)
  .limit(parseInt(limit))

// Count efficiently (uses index scan)
const total = await User.countDocuments({ role: 'admin' })

// Aggregation pipeline for complex queries
const stats = await User.aggregate([
  { $match: { isVerified: true } },
  { $group: { _id: '$role', count: { $sum: 1 } } }
])
```

---

## 7️⃣ React Query Caching (Frontend)

```javascript
const { data } = useQuery({
  queryKey: ['courses'],
  queryFn: fetchCourses,
  staleTime: 5 * 60 * 1000,   // Fresh for 5 minutes (no refetch)
  gcTime: 10 * 60 * 1000,     // Keep in memory 10 minutes (garbage collection time)
  refetchOnWindowFocus: false, // Don't refetch when tab becomes active
})

// Prefetch for faster navigation
const queryClient = useQueryClient()
queryClient.prefetchQuery({
  queryKey: ['course', courseId],
  queryFn: () => fetchCourse(courseId)
})
```

---

## 8️⃣ Performance Monitoring

```javascript
// Measure API response time
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  const start = Date.now()
  res.on('finish', () => {
    const duration = Date.now() - start
    if (duration > 500) {
      console.warn(`SLOW: ${req.method} ${req.path} took ${duration}ms`)
    }
  })
  next()
})
```

**Tools:**
- **Lighthouse** — Browser performance audit
- **Web Vitals** — Google's real user metrics
- **New Relic / Datadog** — Production APM (Application Performance Monitoring)
- **MongoDB Compass** — Query profiler and index analysis

---

## 9️⃣ Compression

```bash
npm install compression
```

```javascript
// Express — gzip compress all responses
const compression = require('compression')
app.use(compression({
  filter: (req, res) => {
    if (req.headers['x-no-compression']) return false
    return compression.filter(req, res)
  },
  level: 6  // 1 (fast) to 9 (best compression), 6 is balanced
}))
```

gzip reduces JSON payloads by 70-80%, making API responses dramatically faster.

---

## 🔟 CDN for Static Assets

```javascript
// next.config.js — serve static assets from CDN
module.exports = {
  assetPrefix: 'https://cdn.yourdomain.com',
  images: {
    domains: ['res.cloudinary.com'],
    formats: ['image/avif', 'image/webp']
  }
}
```

Static assets (JS, CSS, images) cached by CDN — served globally from edge nodes near users.

---

## 💡 Summary

| Layer | Tool/Strategy | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| Browser cache | `Cache-Control` headers | Avoid repeated downloads |
| CDN | Cloudflare, CloudFront | Serve assets from nearest node |
| Server memory | Redis | Sub-millisecond data access |
| Database indexes | `userSchema.index()` | Avoid full collection scans |
| Query optimization | `.select()`, `.lean()` | Reduce data transfer/memory |
| Pagination | `.skip().limit()` | Never return all records |
| Frontend cache | React Query `staleTime` | Avoid duplicate API calls |
| Compression | `compression` middleware | 70-80% smaller responses |
